tweet: So any talk about machines AFTER* paper ballots have already been counted is a special kind of insanity.  (*It’s only a general form of insanity to entertain these discussions BEFORE hand counts or audits.) 4/4

name: Tony Fratto
tweet: In a close election (or if you think it’s “rigged!”), you just count the paper ballots.  Once more: You just count the paper ballots.  In those cases (like Georgia), the machines become completely irrelevant. 3/4

name: Tony Fratto
tweet: A 2nd convenience is that we all get a super accurate unofficial* approximation of the vote more quickly after polls close.  (*Totals are not official until local elections officials conducting canvasses, audits, recounts where necessary, certify the elections.) 2/4

name: Tony Fratto
tweet: AGAIN:  Voting machines producing paper ballots are nothing more than a convenience.  One convenience is voting accuracy, eliminating errors like over-voting.  (Instructions say “Select only one”, but the voter selects 2.) 1/4
